p align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2399<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 6:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/technology/tn_images/arise-corona_150.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
One day my dream of seeing huge telescope mirrors constructed in space might be a reality. Reflector dishes perhaps thousands of kilometres in diameter with near perfect curvature. We will be able to look at hundreds of nearby stars and planets not unlike our own. Best viewing will be when those planets are on the other side of their parent star. So we can get a full surface picture. There may be double star systems with Earthlike worlds which would mean more angles of light. No waiting around for half an exoplanetary year until it can be viewed, perhaps. Will plant life be green or will some other chemical process not involving chlorophyl be employed. Blue trees? Will we be able to make out such tiny details as herds moving across open savannah? Depends on the scale of the mirror. <br>
<br>
After some searching I couldn't find a webpage dealing with this idea. I'll just have to work it out. I'm interested in the size of dish necessary to see exoplanets like Earth in great detail. In space there's no limit to construction but it would be interesting to know the dimensions.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2400<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 7:27 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> The possibilities are endless. With a large enough reflector dish we could see small objects thousands of light years away. Imagine a macroscope aimed at the centre of the milky way. A supermassive blackhole resides there. A sun swallower. Light beams could be turned around back to their origin at a certain distance from the Galactic centre. Stars bend light but a body of that size wraps light right around itself. Anything too close disapears into theoretical science but at a precise point nearby we may see ourselves. Earth as it was 56,000 years ago. For that is how long the light would have taken to reach the hub of our Galaxy then return. An interesting time which reaches far beyond recorded history and civilisation, as far as we know. Seeing it would reveal far more of this age than archaeological debris ever has.<br>
Yes, it would mean a mirror of staggering dimensions but in space you have space and no gravity. It might be a million km wide but only a millimetre thick.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 151<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 11:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> JPL's site on extrasolar worlds:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://planetquest.jpl.nasa.gov/index.html">planetquest.jpl.nasa.gov/index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
The Terrestrial Planet Finder:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://planetquest.jpl.nasa.gov/TPF/tpf_index.html">planetquest.jpl.nasa.gov/...index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
