Kepler: A Search for Habitable Worlds:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://planetquest.jpl.nasa.gov/Kepler/kepler_index.html">planetquest.jpl.nasa.gov/...index.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--> <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=discovery1@nuclearspace>Discovery 1</A> at: 11/10/02 11:58:30 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 368<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 3:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> Interferometry type telescopes are probably the wave of the future since they can give you resolutions similiar to giant mirrors/lenses without having to actually need such bulky devices.  Theoretically, we could deploy a giant fleet of telescopes millions of miles apart to simulate a telescope with a truly immense mirror.  I'm hoping that before I'm fertilizing daffodils that we see an extra-solar planet teeming with life.  It would be a truly inspiring discovery and perhaps the things that would wake us up into realizing that there's a bigger neighborhood out there and that we should strive to become an active part of it.       <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2478<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/15/02 9:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> We have to gather light to build a picture. The more light the bigger the picture. Interferometers wont show us Alien creatures walking around. They can't get the small details. God is in the details. I want to see their faces. I want to know what they look like. Are they smart? What do they do? Fuzzy pictures of a bluey greenish planet with patches of cloud would be ok though. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 416<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/16/02 1:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> A giant fleet of telescopes placed at the areas where the edges of the giant mirror would be could produce images approaching those using a single giant mirror.  Since seeing aliens on extrasolar planets would likely require a mirror AUs in diameter I think interferometery is our only realistic chance for such up close images.  <br>
