 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2531<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/18/02 7:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> Why? If you have the industry to build thousands of small mirrors in space then you can make one large one. I think it would be easier. In space heat can't get away through convection. Only by radiation which is a slow process. Do the shaping in Space. Wire up a sufficient mass of silver to high amperage. After it melts insert a tube and gently blow in Hydrogen until it expands to a balloon. Careful you don't overdo it. Molecular attraction will counter the inner pressure if you don't go overboard. Spin the bubble so it flattens out. When you have the exact shape you want leave it to cool off. You can start off with any size hunk of silver you want.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brp17>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 170<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/21/02 9:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> I don't think we could ever see aliens on other worlds without traveling there. Remember light is produced through finite particles called Photons, and if there isn't enough energy to generate at least one. Hey, wait a second, I just understood astronomy alot more... That's why they expose film for long periods of time on stars, so that random photon will eventually get here. Hmmm. How about that. So I guess it is possible. A mirror in space I would think wouldn't be too terribly hard to make, so long as you can find a way to blow bubbles in a vacuum, and even if that can't be done, then at least a big space station. Still, I think it would be better to build a few smaller ones. The trick is they have to be done ultra-precice, and it's still slightly better to have a large telescope, because while inferometry can detect the presense of objects fairly well, I believe is doesn't have the quality of other methods, but I could be wrong. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2599<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/27/02 10:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=96.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Watching other Earths.</span><hr size=1> I'm sure it can be done. Zero gravity is used to make ball bearing of such perfect shape nothing machined on Earth can match them. This technology is to be employed for gyroscopes which need the best possible ballbearings. I'm just scaling it up. Only existing technology is required. We just have to get the industrial infrastructure into space to make it happen.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left va